## Project Overview

For this project, we are developing a Sleep Tracker program that allows a user to input how many hours they sleep each night over a one-week period. The program then uses that data to generate a graph showing sleep patterns and calculates the average amount of sleep for the week.

The purpose is to be as clear and transparent as possible. 

## Goals

Our goal is to build a program that collects sleep data for seven days, stores it, and displays it in a graph. In addition to the visual output, the program also calculates the weekly average sleep and presents it to the user. If time allows, we may expand the program to include basic feedback based on the results.

## Progress So Far

At this stage, we have finalized the overall design of the program and how each component will function. The program collects the user’s sleep hours for each day of the week, stores the data in a list, and uses that information to calculate the weekly average and generate a graph.

We have implemented the main portions of the code, including user input, data storage, calculations, and graphing. The core functionality is complete and ready to run. While full testing has not yet been completed, the remaining work will focus on debugging and ensuring the program executes smoothly from start to finish.

## Resources Used

We used class notes and examples from lectures to guide the overall structure of the program. We also referenced Python documentation for help with lists and loops, along with online tutorials for using the `matplotlib` library. Online forums were used as needed to troubleshoot small issues.

## Initial Code

```{python}
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

sleep_hours = []

for i in range(7):
    hours = float(input(f"Enter hours of sleep for day {i+1}: "))
    sleep_hours.append(hours)

average_sleep = sum(sleep_hours) / len(sleep_hours)

print("Sleep data:", sleep_hours)
print("Average sleep:", round(average_sleep, 2), "hours")

days = ["Day 1", "Day 2", "Day 3", "Day 4", "Day 5", "Day 6", "Day 7"]

plt.plot(days, sleep_hours, marker='o')
plt.title("Weekly Sleep Tracker")
plt.xlabel("Day")
plt.ylabel("Hours of Sleep")
plt.grid(True)

plt.show()
